 In right triangle \( XYZ \), we are given the lengths of the sides of the right triangle: \( XY = 10 \) (adjacent to angle \( X \)) and \( YZ = 8 \) (opposite to angle \( X \)). The hypotenuse \( XZ \) can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem: \[
XZ = \sqrt{XY^2 + YZ^2} = \sqrt{10^2 + 8^2} = \sqrt{100 + 64} = \sqrt{164} = 2\sqrt{41}
\] The sine of an angle in a right triangle is given by the ratio of the length of the opposite side to the length of the hypotenuse. Therefore, \[
\sin X = \frac{YZ}{XZ} = \frac{8}{2\sqrt{41}} = \frac{4}{\sqrt{41}} = \frac{4\sqrt{41}}{41}
\] </think> <answer> \(\frac{4\sqrt{41}}{41}\) </answer>

